It's like visiting
a friend, Google.

00:03:41.750 --> 00:03:45.190
Because I think
sometimes one or two days

00:03:45.190 --> 00:03:46.720
you don't meet your family.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:48.570
But there's not a single
day when you don't

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:49.808
visit with Google, is there?

00:03:49.808 --> 00:03:51.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:54.550
So it's like coming to
your best friend's house,

00:03:54.550 --> 00:03:58.137
and to a place where
you come in, you

00:03:58.137 --> 00:04:00.470
realize that this is the place
that's changed the world.

00:04:00.470 --> 00:04:02.920
So thank you, thank you
once again, thank you.

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:05.350
SPEAKER: I'd love to get a
little bit more about, you--

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:07.840
and I spoke about
this during lunch--

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:11.770
about music being a passion
versus a profession.

00:04:11.770 --> 00:04:15.520
Your introduction to music
happened at a very young age.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:18.339
At the age of five, you
learned to play instruments.

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:21.110
You've had a very strong
grounding in classical music

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:24.730
before you ventured out,
explored many other areas.

00:04:24.730 --> 00:04:29.640
Tell us a bit more about
why is music so important?

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:32.850
SHANKAR MAHADEVAN: Oh,
my god, I think just

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:39.240
to be able to appreciate
music, and enjoy music,

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:43.370
is, I think, one of the greatest
blessings that you can have.

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:49.880
And above that, if you are in
a position to perform music,

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.695
and if you're in a position
to entertain people

00:04:52.695 --> 00:04:53.570
through your medium--

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:58.290
I think the whole idea of
music is communication.

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:00.060
It's a great form
of communication.

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:06.394
And I think you can
make people laugh.

00:05:06.394 --> 00:05:07.310
You can make them cry.

00:05:07.310 --> 00:05:09.260
You can make them feel inspired.

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:16.124
You can just make a person
who is probably the biggest

00:05:16.124 --> 00:05:18.040
director in a company
just get up on the seat,

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:21.599
and dance, and just forget
about himself, and let go.

00:05:21.599 --> 00:05:22.890
And that is the power of music.

00:05:22.890 --> 00:05:26.480
And if you possess
that power, I think

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:27.860
God blesses you with that.

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:30.650
Very few people get the
blessing that, hey, you

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:32.210
are born to entertain people.

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:35.990
So you can communicate and
give joy, and enjoy something

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:38.840
that we take for granted.

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:40.854
If you're able to
give joy to somebody,

00:05:40.854 --> 00:05:43.020
I think that is the greatest
blessing that you have.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:46.190
And I think we
musicians, every day

00:05:46.190 --> 00:05:48.860
we thank God, that, thank
God I am a musician.

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:51.230
And I'm able to give
happiness to people,

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:56.960
which is something which I
believe in very strongly.

00:05:56.960 --> 00:05:59.030
I was an engineer.

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:00.650
I am an engineer, I can say.

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:02.150
I did my engineering from--

00:06:02.150 --> 00:06:05.410
a lot of my engineering
classmates are here this area.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:09.874
I mean, San Jose, Palo
Alto, maybe even in Fremont.

00:06:09.874 --> 00:06:11.540
In fact, tomorrow I'm
having a breakfast

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:13.460
meeting with all my
engineering buddies.

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:14.650
And I did my engineering.

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:20.390
Though it was fantastic,
and it prepared

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:25.820
me to do a lot of stuff in
life, music was my passion.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:28.220
It was deep within me.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:30.890
And constantly I
had this feeling

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:36.740
that I'm here in this
planet to communicate music

00:06:36.740 --> 00:06:37.990
to the people.

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:40.650
It used to always come to me
again and again and again.

00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:43.640
And of course, then, you're
moving at a great pace.

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:45.030
You're with your friends.

00:06:45.030 --> 00:06:49.014
And you're doing your
schooling, engineering.

00:06:49.014 --> 00:06:51.180
You finish your course and
looking for a [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:51.180 --> 00:06:52.210
interview, all that.

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:54.150
All that is happening.

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:58.400
But at some stage
you have to stop back

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:02.020
and kind of do a little bit
of internal thinking, and say,

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:04.430
hey, is this what
you want to do?

00:07:04.430 --> 00:07:06.250
Or you want to--

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:09.320
there may be like millions
of other engineers

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:12.990
who are 10,000 times
better than you.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.640
Do you want to do something
that you really want to do?

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:18.290
And there were people around me.

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:20.090
My wife, Sangeeta, is here.

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:23.470
I was going around with her
at that time, in my college.

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:26.360
And these are the people
who really stood by me

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:27.310
and said that--

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:30.080
And she did a very important
statement she made,

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:32.130
which really changed
things around.

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:35.120
She said that there may
be a million engineers.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:37.797
But I feel that there will be
only one Shankar Mahadevan.

00:07:37.797 --> 00:07:38.380
She said that.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:39.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:42.662
And I don't know how much
of that is true, but--

00:07:42.662 --> 00:07:44.162
[LAUGHS]

00:07:44.162 --> 00:07:45.620
SPEAKER: You're
definitely somebody

00:07:45.620 --> 00:07:50.630
whose voice is recognized not
only in the hearts of people,

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:52.640
but you're not only
popularized in India,

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:53.820
but you exist in our hearts.

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:54.570
So the statement--

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:58.442
SHANKAR MAHADEVAN: Thank
you, God is more than kind.

00:07:58.442 --> 00:07:59.900
SPEAKER: A question
actually coming

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:02.090
in from a Googler
and a YouTuber.

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:03.330
We are all about--

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:05.560
we are in a generation
where things go viral.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:08.856
We're all about trying to make
things as popular as we are.

00:08:08.856 --> 00:08:11.480
Facebook is about trying to get
as many thousand likes, million

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.430
likes.

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:15.890
Your music, "Breathless," is
one of the most viral videos

00:08:15.890 --> 00:08:17.600
on YouTube.

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:20.060
Tell us a little bit
about music going viral.

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:23.270
Is there a science to
making music going viral?

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:25.669
How do you?

00:08:25.669 --> 00:08:27.710
SHANKAR MAHADEVAN: If that
would have been there,

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:28.962
there was a formula.

00:08:28.962 --> 00:08:30.670
We always think, we
should have a formula

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:32.360
when we are creating the song.

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:36.470
While creating there should be
a red light or a green light.

00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:37.799
So when you're creating, ding!

00:08:37.799 --> 00:08:40.190
The green light goes, oh, this
song is going to be a hit.

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:41.762
If that would have
been possible,

00:08:41.762 --> 00:08:43.220
we would have been
rich and famous.

00:08:43.220 --> 00:08:45.320
You know what I mean?

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:47.810
There's no formula to that.

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:53.090
You have to-- see,
that is the risk

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:55.610
that you take when you
create path-breaking stuff.

00:08:55.610 --> 00:08:58.880
I mean, I'm just saying path
breaking because path breaking,

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:00.650
meaning something
that doesn't exist.

00:09:00.650 --> 00:09:03.110
You always want to
go beyond barriers.

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:07.400
You want to go beyond what you
have done, a benchmark that you

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:09.060
have created for yourself.

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:10.730
So when you're
trying to do that,

00:09:10.730 --> 00:09:13.820
that is as risky as anything.

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:16.490
Either it can be
super successful,

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:19.170
or you can just fall
flat on your face.

00:09:19.170 --> 00:09:23.990
So there is no formula
to doing a viral video.

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:26.660
Because if you try to use
a formula, which means

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:29.090
a formula is something
that already exists.

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:31.130
And you will always
be number two.

00:09:31.130 --> 00:09:32.510
You'll be always compared to--

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:35.210
if I made another "Breathless,"
they will always compare that

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:38.200
to-- oh, at least 50% of the
people over here will say,

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:39.710
[INAUDIBLE],, this
is not like that.

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:41.700
Well, the first one,
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]..

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.720
This is all very
good, but that one?

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:48.350
So you'll never, you'll
never reach that thing.

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:51.260
So I think the
only way you can do

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:57.680
it is try to create
something that doesn't exist.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:59.090
I'm talking musically.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:00.320
I don't know anything else.

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:03.200
So musically, try
to create stuff

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:07.550
that doesn't exist, try to
break your own benchmark,

00:10:07.550 --> 00:10:12.450
try to create new
forms, new sounds, new,

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:15.410
something that even people may
not digest at the beginning.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:20.680
When "Breathless" came out
so many videos were playing.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.640
The indie pop thing was in.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:26.910
The only thing I wanted was,
within the first five seconds,

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:29.630
your reaction should be,
what is this guy doing?

00:10:29.630 --> 00:10:30.340
That's all.

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:34.050
If you got that emotion,
that's more than enough.

00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:36.090
Then you, at least
you can capture

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:37.770
the curiosity of people.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:44.220
And I think you have to do it
passionately and do it full on.

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:48.090
And maybe then, your song,
your video, your piece of music

00:10:48.090 --> 00:10:49.182
may get viral.

00:10:49.182 --> 00:10:50.390
But there's no formula to it.

00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:51.040
I don't think so.

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:51.850
You all know better.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:52.808
What are you asking me?

00:10:52.808 --> 00:10:53.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:56.019
SPEAKER: We thought we might
learn something from you.

00:10:57.920 --> 00:10:59.430
Actually asking
you a question, you

00:10:59.430 --> 00:11:03.990
have been a part of one of the
most successful musical trios

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:08.190
that India has seen
with Ehsaan and Loy.

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:09.850
Tell us a little
bit more about that,

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:12.150
because it's an industry
where styles of music

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:13.770
can be so variable.

00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:15.510
Egos are fragile.

00:11:15.510 --> 00:11:17.070
How did you form
that partnership?

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:19.832
And what made it so successful?

00:11:19.832 --> 00:11:21.290
SHANKAR MAHADEVAN:
This is actually

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:22.581
a very interesting partnership.

00:11:22.581 --> 00:11:25.190
And we, ourselves, are
very amazed at the way

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.670
we have sustained, because
we have completed 21

00:11:28.670 --> 00:11:30.040
years of composing this year.

00:11:30.040 --> 00:11:30.623
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:11:30.623 --> 00:11:32.762
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:37.470
SHANKAR MAHADEVAN: We
started off 21 years back.

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:43.960
And we three are completely
different individuals,

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:47.650
characteristics-wise and
musical preferences-wise,

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:51.950
temperament-wise,
choices, whatever.

00:11:51.950 --> 00:11:55.330
The way we are, we are
three different individuals.

00:11:55.330 --> 00:11:57.230
We have nothing in common.

00:11:57.230 --> 00:11:59.230
But that is the beauty.

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:02.990
When you look at
a piece of music,

00:12:02.990 --> 00:12:06.070
it's like a melody is created.

00:12:06.070 --> 00:12:07.780
And you're looking
at that melody

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:11.920
from three different angles,
using three different cameras.

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:13.960
So what I see, he doesn't see.

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:15.580
And what he sees,
he doesn't see.

00:12:15.580 --> 00:12:20.120
